  "prompt": "What are some ways to restore a Compaq computer to factory settings?",
  "response": "Restoring a Compaq computer to factory settings depends largely on the operating system it's running.  Here's a breakdown of methods, covering different eras of Compaq machines, with some important warnings up front:\n\n**IMPORTANT WARNINGS BEFORE YOU START:**\n\n*   **Data Loss:**  Factory resets will ERASE EVERYTHING on your hard drive. Back up any important documents, photos, music, videos, and other files before you begin. If the computer won't boot, you may need to remove the hard drive and use another computer to try and recover data (requires an external drive enclosure).\n*   **Product Keys:**  Make sure you have the product key for your operating system and any other software you need to reinstall. This is especially crucial for older Windows versions. Sometimes the key is on a sticker on the computer case, but it's better to have it documented elsewhere.\n*   **Drivers:** If you're using an older operating system (Windows XP or older) after the factory restore, you will likely need to install drivers for your hardware to work properly. Have a driver disc or a way to download drivers from the internet ready, such as a USB drive with the appropriate drivers.\n*   **Power Supply:**  Ensure your Compaq laptop is plugged into a power source during the entire process. Interrupting the reset can lead to corruption of the operating system.\n*   **BIOS/UEFI:** Do NOT interrupt or power off the computer during any BIOS or UEFI process, which can cause irreparable damage to the motherboard.\n\n**Methods, By Operating System:**\n\n**1.  Windows XP (and Earlier): Recovery Partition (if present) or Recovery Discs**\n\n   *   **Recovery Partition (If Available):**\n        *   **Identifying a Recovery Partition:**  Older Compaq computers often had a hidden recovery partition containing the factory image.  Look for a specific key to press during boot. This key is *very* model-specific. Some common keys to try, but may not work for your model, are F10, F11, F12 or CTRL+F11. The boot screen should indicate the key to press to launch the recovery utility. If you can find your specific model manual it will indicate the key to use.\n        *   **Booting to Recovery:** If you can find the key, restart the computer. Immediately and repeatedly press the identified key during the boot process, until you see a Compaq recovery utility start.\n        *   **Following On-Screen Instructions:** The recovery utility will guide you through the process.  It will likely ask if you want to restore to factory settings.  Be very sure you understand what you're doing before confirming.\n\n   *   **Recovery Discs:**\n        *   **Locate the Discs:**  If you have them, use the recovery discs that came with the computer. These discs will contain the original factory image.\n        *   **Boot from the Disc:**  Insert the first disc into the CD/DVD drive.  You may need to adjust the boot order in the BIOS to boot from the CD/DVD drive.\n        *   **Follow On-Screen Instructions:** The recovery program will start and guide you through the restoration process.\n\n   * **No Recovery Partition or Discs?**:\n        *   You'll need to obtain a Windows XP (or appropriate OS) install disc and perform a clean installation. This requires a valid product key. You will also have to manually install all the drivers, which can be difficult.\n\n**2. Windows Vista/7: Compaq Recovery Manager**\n\n   *   **Accessing Compaq Recovery Manager:**\n        *   **From Within Windows (If Windows Boots):**\n            1.  Click the Start button.\n            2.  Type \"recovery\" in the search bar.\n            3.  Look for \"Compaq Recovery Manager\" or \"HP Recovery Manager\" (Compaq was acquired by HP).\n            4.  Select the program.\n        *   **From Boot (If Windows Doesn't Boot):**\n            1.  Restart the computer.\n            2.  Repeatedly press the F11 key during boot. This should launch the Compaq Recovery Manager.  Again, this is model-dependent.  Consult the user manual for your specific model if F11 doesn't work.\n\n   *   **Using Recovery Manager:**\n        *   **Follow On-Screen Prompts:**  The Recovery Manager will present options such as \"Factory Reset,\" \"System Recovery,\" or similar.\n        *   **Choose Factory Reset (or similar):** Select the option to restore the computer to its original factory state.\n        *   **Follow the Instructions Carefully:** The process can take a while. Ensure the computer remains powered on.\n\n**3. Windows 8/8.1/10/11: Built-in Windows Reset Feature**\n\n   *   **From Within Windows:**\n        1.  Click the Start button.\n        2.  Type \"reset\" in the search bar.\n        3.  Select \"Reset this PC.\"\n        4.  Choose \"Remove everything\" or \"Remove files and clean the drive\" for a complete factory reset.  (Note: \"Remove files and clean the drive\" is more secure, but takes significantly longer.)\n        5.  Follow the on-screen prompts.  You may be asked to choose between a cloud download of Windows or a local reinstall.  A local reinstall is typically faster.  Cloud download might be necessary if your recovery partition is damaged.\n\n   *   **From Boot (If Windows Doesn't Boot):**\n        1.  Restart the computer.\n        2.  If the PC doesn't start normally, after 2 or 3 attempts, Windows should automatically boot into the Windows Recovery Environment (WinRE).\n        3.  From the WinRE menu, select \"Troubleshoot\" -> \"Reset this PC.\"\n        4.  Follow the on-screen prompts, as described above.\n\n**Troubleshooting:**\n\n*   **Recovery Partition Corrupted:** If the recovery partition is damaged, the F11 key (or equivalent) won't work. You may need to use Windows installation media (DVD or USB) to reinstall Windows. If you do not have install media, you can download it from Microsoft's website, but will require a product key.\n*   **Missing Drivers:** After a factory reset, you might need to install drivers for devices like the network adapter, graphics card, sound card, etc.  Download these drivers from the Compaq (now HP) support website using the model number of your computer.\n*   **Activation Issues:** If you're prompted to activate Windows and you don't have a product key, contact Microsoft support.  For older versions, it might be impossible to activate.\n*   **BIOS Issues:** *Never* interrupt a BIOS update or reset. This can brick your motherboard.\n\n**Finding Your Compaq Model Number:**\n\nThe model number is usually found on a sticker on the bottom of a laptop or on the side or back of a desktop.  It's crucial for finding the correct drivers and documentation.\n\n**Recommendation:**\n\nBefore proceeding with any factory reset, search online for information specific to *your* Compaq model.  Look for user manuals or forum posts that discuss the recovery process.  This will help you identify the correct key to press during boot and avoid potential problems.\n",
